Dominic Andrla v Ricardo Villanueva
[2023] SGDC 81

Case Number:District Court Suit No 1112 of 2020
Decision Date:28 April 2023
Tribunal/Court:District Court
Coram: Tan May Tee
Counsel Name(s): Wee Heng Yi Adrian and Lynette Chang (Lighthouse LLC) for the plaintiff; Remy Choo Zheng Xi (Remy Choo Chambers LLC) (instructed) and Wong Thai Yong (Skandan Law LLC) (instructed) with Choy Wing Kin Montague (Imperial Law LLC) for the defendant.
Parties: Dominic Andrla — Ricardo Villanueva

Contract – Oral agreement

Evidence – Burden of proof

Evidence – Admissibility of evidence – Whether correspondence subject to “without prejudice” privilege

28 April 2023

District Judge Tan May Tee:

Introduction

1       The plaintiff is a British citizen, and a permanent resident of Singapore. The defendant is a Singapore citizen[note: 1]. The parties have known each other for over 20 years.

2       The plaintiff was the founder and sole shareholder of Straits Advisors Pte Ltd (“SAPL”), a company providing financial consultancy services. In terms of its corporate structure, SAPL was wholly owned by another entity, Straits Advisors Group Ltd (“SAGL”), of which the plaintiff was also the sole shareholder[note: 2].

3       In 1998, when the plaintiff was the consultant chief financial officer of a tech startup company called FailSafe Corporation (Singapore) Pte Ltd, he had recruited the defendant to work with him at the startup company[note: 3]. In January 2003, the plaintiff then employed the defendant to work for SAPL to do corporate finance advisory work essentially handling mergers and acquisitions. Sometime during his employment, the defendant was made an executive director of SAPL[note: 4].

4       SAPL ran into financial difficulties sometime in 2011. The defendant resigned from the company in April 2015. SAPL was wound up shortly after in July 2015[note: 5].

5       In this suit, the plaintiff seeks to recover the sum of $177,000 from the defendant in respect of what he claims were two interest-free “friendly loans” requested by the defendant. The first loan was for $87,000 (“1st Loan”) while the second loan was for $90,000 (“2nd Loan”) and paid over four tranches.

6       The defendant denies the plaintiff’s claim entirely. He says that the 1st Loan was in fact the plaintiff’s partial repayment to him of a loan of $96,500 which he had extended to the plaintiff (“the 2011 Loan”) while the 2nd Loan was the plaintiff’s payment of outstanding salaries owed to him by SAPL.

7       At the trial, the only witnesses were the plaintiff and the defendant. Having considered their testimonies in conjunction with the relevant documentary evidence, and the submissions of both counsel, I dismiss the plaintiff’s claim. My reasons are set out herein.

The plaintiff’s case

8       The plaintiff’s statement of claim pleads very simply as follows:

3.    In or about early May 2014, the Defendant approached the Plaintiff for an interest-free, friendly loan which would be repayable on demand. The Plaintiff agreed to do so on the terms proposed by the Defendant. On or about 14 May 2014, the Plaintiff disbursed the sum of S$87,000.00 (the “1st Loan”) to the Defendant.

4.    Subsequently, in or about October or November 2014, the Defendant informed the Plaintiff that he was experiencing continuing financial difficulties and requested that the Plaintiff extend further interest-free friendly loans to him. Pursuant to the Defendant’s request, the Plaintiff agreed to extend further loans to the Defendant, repayable on demand, which were disbursed in the following manner:

(a)    The sum of S$50,000.00 on or about 3 November 2014;

(b)    The sum of S$30,000.00 on or about 24 December 2014;

(c)    The sum of S$5,000.00 on or about 3 February 2015;

(d)    The sum of S$5,000.00 on or about 13 March 2015.

(collectively, the “2nd Loan”)

5.    The total sum of S$177,000.00, being the aggregate of the 1st and 2nd Loans, remains due and owing by the Defendant to the Plaintiff to date. Despite several demands for repayment, the said sum of S$177,000.00 remains due and owing. Further and/or in the alternative, this action constitutes a demand for repayment of both the 1st and 2nd Loans.

9       The plaintiff’s claim that the friendly loans were requested is premised on oral requests and/or agreements made by the defendant because of his financial difficulties at the material time in May 2014 and subsequently in October and November 2014.

10     In his AEIC, the plaintiff gave the following account as to how the 1st Loan came into existence in May 2014:

(a)     In 2011, SAPL experienced financial difficulties due to poor cash flow. It needed approximately $253,000 for salary and other expenses. SAPL and the defendant agreed that the defendant would extend a loan of $96,500 to SAPL (ie the 2011 Loan). This loan was to be repayable on demand when SAPL’s cash flow improved. The remaining amount of $157,400 required by SAPL was funded by SAGL.

(b)     The plaintiff is unaware as to why the defendant had agreed to extend the 2011 Loan to SAPL. He surmised that it was also in the defendant’s financial interests that SAPL remained afloat so as to be able to pay the defendant’s salary which was then at approximately $27,500 per month.

(c)     In about early May 2014, some three years after the defendant extended the 2011 Loan to SAPL, the defendant informed the plaintiff that he was in financial difficulty. He requested an interest-free, friendly loan repayable on demand.

(d)     The plaintiff agreed and disbursed the sum of $87,000 to the defendant by way of a telegraphic transfer from his account with the United Overseas Bank Ltd (“UOB”) to the defendant’s UOB account.

11     As for the 2nd Loan, it transpired in this manner – in or about October or November 2014, the defendant informed the plaintiff that he continued to be in financial difficulty. He requested a further interest-free, friendly loan repayable on demand. The plaintiff obliged and disbursed a total of $90,000 to the defendant by way of fund transfers from his UOB account to the defendant’s UOB account comprising $50,000 on 3 November 2014, $30,000 on 24 December 2014, $5,000 on 3 February 2015 and $5,000 on 13 March 2015[note: 6].

The defendant’s case

12     In his defence, the defendant pleaded that he was never monetarily indebted to the plaintiff. The payments made to him were repayments of the 2011 Loan. This was a personal loan which he had given to the plaintiff and had come about in the following manner:

(a)     Around late February to early March 2011, the plaintiff approached him and verbally asked for a loan of $96,500. The plaintiff informed him that SAPL had cashflow issues and needed money for its operations. This was not the first time that the plaintiff had reached out to him for loans.

(b)     As the defendant did not have enough cash to fund the requested loan, the plaintiff asked him to take out loans from different banks to obtain the cash to loan to him. The plaintiff agreed to repay all the interest that he would incur on such loans. As this arrangement had been adhered to in the past, upon the plaintiff’s confirmation that he would repay the loans and the interest, the defendant took out the following loans to fund the $96,500 requested by the plaintiff:

(i)       $34,900 from DBS Bank Ltd (“DBS”) on 24 February 2011;

(ii)       $28,400 from Citibank Singapore Ltd (“Citibank”) on 25 February 2011; and

(iii)       $33,200 from Australia and New Zealand Banking Group Ltd (“ANZ”) on 1 March 2011.

13     As a result of the 2011 Loan given the plaintiff, the defendant became debt laden to various banks. This was because the initial loans taken out carried promotional rates of interest for a limited time only. When the loans were not repaid, the defendant took out further loans under new facilities so as to avoid paying default interest rates. When the plaintiff failed to repay the loans in a timely manner, the defendant then started taking out fixed term loans which carried lower interest rates instead of loans from overdraft facilities so as to have the payments spread out over a longer period.

14     The defendant would constantly ask the plaintiff to repay the loans. On or about 14 May 2014, the plaintiff transferred the sum of $87,000 to the defendant which he then used to make repayment of some of the outstanding loans.

The plaintiff signed loan agreement and made payments to the defendant

15     Over time, the defendant became increasingly uncomfortable on the amount of liability that he was incurring on the plaintiff’s behalf as well as the fact that none of it was in writing. Further, the salaries due to him from SAPL were also starting to build up. On or around 31 October 2014, he asked the plaintiff to sign a written agreement to “memorialise” their loan arrangement (“Written Loan Agreement”) which the plaintiff agreed.

16     Clauses 1, 2, 3 and 4 of the Written Loan Agreement state as follows:

1.     The Loan

The Lender agrees to lend and the Borrower agrees to borrow a sum of $158,775 (Singapore dollar one hundred fifty-eight thousand seven hundred and seventy-five only) as at 31 October 2014.

2.     Interest

The Borrower agrees to pay interest on the loan to the Lender with variable rate. The Lender is entitled to charge the interest rate at any time by informing the Borrower in writing. However, the (sic) initially the interest rate shall be set at 2 percent per month (“Interest Rate”). For the avoidance of doubt, the Interest Rate is compounded monthly.

3.     Repayment of the loan

The Lender is entitled to make a request (sic) the Borrower to repay the principal sum and interest of the loan to the Lender at any time.

4.     Assignment

This Agreement shall be binding on and inure to the benefit of the parties of this Agreement and their respective successors and assigns. Without the Borrower’s consent, the Lender may by notice in writing to the Borrower at any time assign to any assignee(s) all or any part of its rights under this Agreement. But the rights of the Borrower under this Agreement are personal to it and cannot be assigned either in whole or in part.

17     The defendant explained that $158,775 was the amount of the principal sum of the 2011 Loan ie $96,500 plus compounded interest to the various financial institutions which the defendant was servicing as at 31 October 2014, less the sums which the plaintiff had already repaid the defendant at that point. The defendant had obtained this figure by calling up the different banks to which the loans were outstanding and confirming the sum he would have had to repay if he were to redeem the loans as at 31 October 2014[note: 7].

18     As for the interest rate, it was calculated at approximately 2% per month compounded monthly to simplify the agreement due to some loans which had interest rates higher than 2% and some lower than 2%[note: 8].

19     While the Written Loan Agreement had been signed in October 2014, the plaintiff did not make any repayments until the defendant requested him to do so again in January 2016. The plaintiff made partial repayments to the defendant of $10,000 on 21 January 2016, $5,000 on 16 March 2016, $1,000 on 1 May 2016 and $1,000 on or about 23 June 2016[note: 9].

20     A further 23 payments were made on various dates from 12 August 2016 to 7 February 2017 totalling $53,250[note: 10].

The defendant sued the plaintiff for repayment under the Written Loan Agreement

21     From 7 February 2017, despite the defendant’s numerous requests for payment, the plaintiff failed to make any further payment of the loan.

22     In August 2017, the defendant instructed solicitors and commenced DC 2271/2017 against the plaintiff claiming the amount of $226,553.00, being the amount outstanding under the Written Loan Agreement less the sums already repaid by the plaintiff up to that point.

23     On 26 January 2018, the plaintiff’s solicitors wrote to the Registrar, State Courts to inform that the plaintiff had been adjudged a bankrupt on 25 January 2018, and sought the vacation of an upcoming hearing against the plaintiff. On account of the plaintiff’s bankruptcy, the defendant did not proceed further with DC 2271/2017 and on 19 March 2019 it was deemed discontinued[note: 11].

The defendant’s suit was compromised by the plaintiff’s IVA

24     Unknown to the defendant at that time, the plaintiff was taking steps to reverse his bankruptcy status. After a previous failed attempt, the plaintiff succeeded in obtaining an Interim Order pursuant to s 45 Bankruptcy Act 1995 to enter into an individual voluntary arrangement (“IVA”) with the support of his major creditors. A creditors’ meeting was called by his appointed nominee (“Nominee”) under the IVA.

25     The defendant submitted his proof of debt for the sum of $226,553.00, being the amount outstanding under the written loan agreement. The Nominee, however, rejected the claim and was prepared to admit only the sum of $29,250 which was the principal amount of $96,500 and set off against the payments that the defendant had received. The Nominee’s reason for rejecting the defendant’s claim was that the Written Loan Agreement was “unenforceable as a loan granted by an unlicensed moneylender under the Moneylenders Act”[note: 12]. Notably, this was one of the several defences that the plaintiff had mounted against the defendant’s claim in DC 2271/2017[note: 13].

26     Despite the defendant’s disagreement with the Nominee, the admitted debt stood at $29,250 only. The defendant had placed his objections on record and also disclosed that he had received payment of a further sum of $3,000 which the Nominee had omitted and invited the Nominee to amend his adjudication of the defendant’s claim. The Nominee refused[note: 14].

27     The defendant decided not to challenge the Nominee’s adjudication as he felt that the costs were prohibitive and the scope of recovery against the plaintiff was limited given that the plaintiff’s indebtedness at that time stood at over $20 million[note: 15].

28     When the plaintiff instituted this suit, the defendant had initially made a counterclaim against the plaintiff for repayment of the balance outstanding amount and accrued interest pursuant to the Written Loan Agreement. The counterclaim was, however, struck off on the basis that it had been compromised by the proof of debt submitted by the defendant which was accepted by the plaintiff’s Nominee as documented in his IVA report.

The 2nd Loan was the plaintiff’s payment of the defendant’s salaries

29     As for the plaintiff’s alleged 2nd Loan of $90,000, the defendant pleads that the amounts disbursed by the plaintiff were payments for salary arrears owed to him. As at end October 2014, SAPL owed the defendant a cumulative sum of $106,000 being the outstanding salaries from July 2014 to October 2014[note: 16].

30     The defendant testified that SAPL, being in the business of mergers and acquisitions, did not have a steady revenue stream as its cashflow was dependent on when deals closed. Consequently, he was paid his salary by SAPL and/or the plaintiff as and when there were funds. There were months when he did not receive any salary and others when the plaintiff or SAPL would pay partially or fully what was owed to him[note: 17].

31     According to the defendant, SAPL was effectively the plaintiff’s alter ego which the plaintiff had used to shield himself from liability whenever it was convenient for him to do so. An example of this was the position taken by the plaintiff in DC 2271/2017. In that suit, the plaintiff had pleaded that the 2011 Loan extended to him in March 2011 was SAPL’s loan and not his. However, in the plaintiff’s application for discharge from his bankruptcy, he then resiled from that position and claimed that the loan was owed by him personally as set out in the Nominee’s report. This was not only dishonest, but also beneficial to the plaintiff since by subsuming SAPL’s purported indebtedness under the IVA, this effectively extinguished his debt to the defendant once the IVA was approved[note: 18].

32     The defendant pointed out that the plaintiff, as SAPL’s sole shareholder, had no qualms about paying him his salary from his own pocket[note: 19].

33     The defendant further testified that at the time of his resignation on 11 April 2015, there was a sum of $153,217 owing to him as unpaid salary. As the parties were then still on good terms, when the plaintiff approached him to write off what was owed to him, he agreed. The plaintiff’s outstanding loan to him with the accumulating interest was snowballing and he knew that the plaintiff could not afford to pay him on both fronts. He therefore agreed to forego the outstanding salaries from SAPL so that the plaintiff could more quickly pay off the loan owed to him[note: 20].

34     It was agreed that the outstanding salaries be written off by retrospectively halving the defendant’s salary in 2014 such that SAPL’s debt to the defendant would be reduced by $153,000 which was almost the amount owed to the defendant. Amended employment letters dated 1 January 2014 (halving the defendant’s salary to $13,750) and 1 January 2015 (restoring the salary from $13,750 to $27,500) were prepared and signed at the time of his departure on 11 April 2015 for this purpose. The remainder of $217 was also written off by the defendant[note: 21].

35     The defendant explained that the agreement with the plaintiff for the halving of his salary had taken into account the $90,000 paid by the plaintiff as his salary payments as demonstrated by the tabulations that he included in his AEIC[note: 22].

Issues

36     From their respective pleaded cases and the submissions tendered, the parties agreed that the issues presented for the court’s determination are:

(a)     Whether the 1st Loan was a loan extended by the plaintiff to the defendant or a part repayment by the plaintiff of the 2011 Loan; and

(b)     Whether the 2nd Loan was a loan extended by the plaintiff to the defendant or a payment by the plaintiff of salaries owed by SAPL to the defendant.

37     At the commencement of the trial, the plaintiff had raised an objection to various correspondence that had been referred to and included in the defendant’s AEIC on the ground that these were without prejudice communications between the parties. A preliminary issue was raised as to the admissibility of these documents which will be dealt with first before a deliberation of the two substantive issues.

Preliminary issue – whether the defendant’s email correspondence is protected by “without prejudice” privilege

38     The plaintiff’s specific objection, as documented in his notice of objections to the contents of the defendant’s AEIC, pertains to emails sent by the defendant to the plaintiff on 7 August 2016 at 5:25pm and 14 July 2016 at 8.27pm, 8.16pm and 2.52pm under the subject title, “Loans Outstanding as at 13 July 2016”[note: 23]. This is because in a subsequent email sent by the defendant to the plaintiff timestamped Friday 16 August 2016 at 5.03am, the defendant had stated as follows,

Dear Dominic

You must be travelling or else I would have certainly heard from you. Since you have not replied yet, I should add that my emails below which you have yet to reply to are sent WITHOUT PREJUDICE. In particular, I wish to highlight the loan agreement which you signed with me on 31 Oct 2014.

I sincerely hope we can move forward based on what we agree is the best way forward.

Best regards,

Ricardo

39     Mr Adrian Wee (“Mr Wee”), counsel for the plaintiff, argued that the correspondence which the defendant had sought to refer to had been described as “without prejudice” and save where there are express exceptions in the email chain, such correspondence cannot be referred to in these proceedings. He argued that contained within the correspondence were attempts at resolving the outstanding dispute, in particular the repayment of the loan. The correspondence was protected by privilege notwithstanding that it is in fact the defendant who is making the disclosure of his “without prejudice” communications.

40     Mr Wong Thai Yong (“Mr Wong”), one of the counsel instructed by the defendant, took the court through the email chain to show that while the email contained discussions about the manner of repayment, there is no dispute that there were monies owing from the plaintiff to the defendant and that repayments were to be made. Mr Wong submitted that the present case is on all-fours with the facts in Cytec Industries Pte Ltd v APP Chemicals International (Mau) Ltd [2009] 4 SLR(R) 769 (“Cytec”) where the court, on examining the correspondence, found that it contained an implied admission by the defendant as to the existence of the debt and liability for it. There was no dispute as to liability or quantum, and accordingly no ongoing dispute that would attract the application of the “without prejudice” privilege.

41     It is trite that the attachment of a “without prejudice” label without more to a document would not automatically render it privileged although it would lead to the prima facie inference that the document was intended to be a negotiating document. See Cytec [16] and [17]. Whether or not “without prejudice” privilege attaches must be determined by objectively construing the documents as a whole in the context of the factual circumstances.

42     Looking at the chain of emails in question, I agree with Mr Wong’s submission that there is nothing there which suggests that there is any dispute between the parties as to the fact that there were monies owing by the plaintiff to the defendant. Notably, the very title of the email chain bears the description “Loans Outstanding as at 13 July 2016”. The first email in the chain makes express reference to the 31 October 2014 Written Loan Agreement signed by the plaintiff for the sum of $158,775 and also makes express mention of the monthly interest accruing at 2% per month. What follows after the first email are nothing more than proposals for repayment of the outstanding loans by instalments.

43     As succinctly put by Ang J in Cytec at [17], “… it is the existence of a dispute and an attempt to compromise it that was at the heart of the “without prejudice” privilege.” The contents of the email chain referred to by the defendant (at pages 164 to 166 of his AEIC) do not evince any dispute between the parties as to liability for the loans nor their quantum and would not attract the policy justification for “without prejudice” privilege. Accordingly, the plaintiff’s objection fails.

Whether the 1st Loan was a loan extended by the plaintiff to the defendant or a part repayment by the plaintiff of the 2011 Loan

44     As pleaded by the plaintiff, the 1st Loan is the sum of $87,000 disbursed to the defendant in May 2014. The only evidence that this payment was a loan to the defendant lies in the plaintiff’s assertions in his AEIC at [21] and [22]. There is no documentary evidence that the plaintiff has adduced to support his claim that any request for an interest-free friendly loan was made by the defendant.

45     In these circumstances, it cannot be disputed that the principles to guide the court in determining the existence of an oral agreement to grant a “friendly loan” to the defendant are those as set out in ARS v ART [2015] SGHC 78 (and applied in Naughty G Pte Ltd v Fortune Marketing Pte Ltd [2018] 5 SLR 1208 at [56]), namely:

(a)    in ascertaining the existence of an oral agreement, the court will consider the relevant documentary evidence (such as written correspondence) and contemporaneous conduct of the parties at the material time;

(b)    where possible, the court should look first at the relevant documentary evidence;

(c)    the availability of relevant documentary evidence reduces the need to rely solely on the credibility of witnesses in order to ascertain if an oral agreement exists;

(d)    oral testimony may be less reliable as it is based on the witness’ recollection and it may be affected by subsequent events (such as the dispute between the parties);

(e)    credible oral testimony may clarify the existing documentary evidence;

(f)    where the witness is not legally trained, the court should not place undue emphasis on the choice of words; and

(g)    if there is little or no documentary evidence, the court will nevertheless examine the precise factual matrix to ascertain if there is an oral agreement concluded between the parties

The documentary evidence and contemporaneous conduct do not show a loan requested by the defendant

46     The documentary evidence adduced by the plaintiff on the 1st Loan is limited solely to the debit advice from UOB showing that the sum of $87,000 had been debited in favour of the defendant[note: 24]. Other than the fact that the sum of $87,000 had been transferred from the plaintiff’s account to the defendant, there is not a single piece of evidence that has been adduced to support the plaintiff’s assertion that this amount was a loan to the defendant.

47     As against the dearth of evidence on the side of the plaintiff, the defendant has produced overwhelming evidence showing that:

(a)     The plaintiff had agreed by way of the Written Loan Agreement that he was personally indebted to the defendant.

(b)     The plaintiff did not at any time refute the numerous correspondence (text messages and emails) which show that the defendant was in fact chasing him for payment of the loans taken out for the plaintiff’s benefit.

(c)     The plaintiff had made various partial repayments of the debt owed to the defendant pursuant to his requests for payment.

The Written Loan Agreement

48     The Written Loan Agreement explicitly identifies the plaintiff as the borrower and the defendant as lender. It categorically sets out the plaintiff’s liability as borrower for a specified sum of $158,775 together with interest at a variable rate. Given these clear terms, the plaintiff’s verbal assertions, without more, are woefully inadequate to prove that he was not meant to be personally liable for the loan.

49     Additionally, the Nominee in the IVA had admitted the debt under the Written Loan Agreement to be the plaintiff’s personal debt and not that of SAPL albeit to a much smaller extent than what the defendant had claimed. The genesis of this debt was the 2011 Loan of $96,500 given by the defendant to the plaintiff as pleaded in his statement of claim in DC 2271/2017 which had been sighted by the Nominee. By his acceptance of the debt, the Nominee would also have accepted that the Written Loan Agreement was in respect of the personal loan of $96,500 given by the defendant to the plaintiff in 2011. Given the position taken by the Nominee, it is untenable for the plaintiff to continue canvassing the position that the liability for the 2011 Loan was that of SAPL and not his.

50     Notably, during cross-examination on the various messages from the defendant asking for payment, the plaintiff himself had recognised that the contradictory position he had taken was no longer viable, see extract below[note: 25]:

Q    Yes. So, page 312, this is now August and Mr Villanueva is, again telling you: look, I need funds. You do not deny personal liability for the funds and, in fact, transferred $2,000, correct?

A    Correct.

Q    Okay. So, you agree here that as of 12th August 2016, you understood correctly that you were personally liable for the loans to Mr Villanueva that he had taken out on your behalf in 2011, correct?

A    I have repeatedly disputed that position. What I have said is the loans were to the company and I was trying my - because the company had gone into liquidation - I was trying my best to help Mr Villanueva. As I have already said, it is kind of irrelevant, as the nominee later said I was liable by the October agreement in any case, so.

(emphasis in italics mine)

The defendant’s text messages and emails

51     The defendant has adduced evidence by way of numerous text messages exchanged with the plaintiff spanning from December 2015 to March 2017[note: 26] showing that he had repeatedly asked the plaintiff for repayment of the outstanding amounts owed to the banks which had come about from the 2011 Loan. If the plaintiff’s account were true ie that the loan was SAPL’s liability and not his, given the fact that SAPL had been wound up by this time, it begs the question why throughout the entire course of the text communications between the parties there is not even a single demur from the plaintiff that he has no legal liability for the Loan.

52     The defendant’s messages and desperate pleas for payment provide more than ample support that the debt owed was the plaintiff’s personal debt. Given the relatively casual nature of such communications, it seems to me most improbable that the plaintiff would not have provided any hint of his position that this was SAPL’s debt and not his. In fact, his replies to the defendant coupled by part payments made indicate an admission of the debt, as illustrated by the exchange reproduced below[note: 27]:

53     There was no payment made the following month, February 2016, and the defendant’s plea for repayment of the 2011 Loan was again reiterated in March 2016[note: 28] to which there was no denial from the plaintiff and his response was merely that it would be difficult for him to make any payments in the next couple of weeks:

54     The defendant’s increasing desperation for some respite from the plaintiff for the liability he had incurred due to the loans extended to the plaintiff was articulated yet again in April 2016 and was not met with any demur or disagreement from the plaintiff despite his own dire circumstances at that time[note: 29]:

55     When the plaintiff did refer to the loans as “company loans” in May 2016, this was refuted by the defendant at the earliest opportunity, that they were personal loans to him, with no follow-up response by the plaintiff [note: 30]:

56     Inexplicably, the plaintiff had also agreed to a payment plan of a fixed sum of $13,000 at a meeting between the two men in August 2016 which would start in September 2016[note: 31]. For avoidance of doubt, I do not consider any of the correspondence exhibited by the defendant in his AEIC as regards the plaintiff’s proposal for repayment to be without prejudice for the same reasons set out at [42] and [43] above.

57     It appears that the plaintiff was unable to adhere to the payment plan which led to further messages from the defendant clearly venting his frustration, see example below[note: 32]:

58     It is significant that the defendant’s reference to the plaintiff’s agreement to pay $13,107 each month was not disputed in any of the plaintiff’s replies. His responses were typically that he would provide an update when he had the available funds and how much he could transfer to the defendant.

59     The defendant’s requests for payment continued unabated in January 2017 when the plaintiff’s payments did not materialise as promised. In fact, the plaintiff had even expressed his hope that that he would try to bring his payments “up to date”, see below[note: 33]:

60     The defendant’s references to the debt obligation of the plaintiff were again not refuted, and the defendant had even gone to the extent of suggesting that the plaintiff surrender his Tanglin Club membership to raise funds[note: 34]:

61     When payments were not received, the defendant gave an ultimatum. Notably, the plaintiff’s reply was an admission that they had an agreed payment schedule that he had defaulted on, see below[note: 35]. At no time did the plaintiff refute the defendant’s statement that he was the one doing the plaintiff a favour by trying to manage the plaintiff’s debt with the banks:

62     Given the plaintiff’s professional background and experience – he is reportedly a Harvard graduate, has worked at Rothschild[note: 36], and was a senior manager with HSBC Investment Asia Pte Ltd with more than 30 years of corporate finance experience in Asia and Europe before starting SAPL/SAGL – it seems to me incredible that:

(a)     he would go to the extent of making a firm commitment to pay a monthly sum of $13,107 without any indication that this was done merely out of a moral obligation on his part and at the behest of the defendant;

(b)     he would subject himself to the continued onslaught of demands and threats from the defendant which could objectively be regarded as harassment when he failed to honour his repayment schedule; and

(c)     he would continue to promise the defendant that he would be remitting funds for the loan repayment.

63     The evidence presented from the pattern of correspondence between the parties points overwhelmingly towards a loan obligation by the plaintiff, and not SAPL, to the defendant. It also points indisputably to a debt obligation by the plaintiff to the defendant, and not the other way round.

Plaintiff did not have the financial means to extend any loans to the defendant

64     During cross-examination, the plaintiff admitted that in 2014 he was heavily indebted. In the circumstances, he would not be in the position to make any loans to the defendant, as shown from the following excerpt[note: 37]:

Q    … Mr Andrla, in 2014, am I correct to say that you were quite heavily indebted, you owed quite a few people a lot of money?

A    Yes. That is correct.

Q    One of these people you owed money to was one Mr Harry Nyre(?) (sic), correct?

A    That is correct.

Q    Who lent you US$1.6 million in August 2014, correct?

A    That is correct.

Q    Right. You also owed banks quite a sum of money, correct?

A    Correct.

Q    And you also had a mortgage on a property you were paying, correct?

A    Correct.

Q    This was the Lotus Avenue property, correct?

A    Correct.

Q    The Lotus Avenue property was worth about $10 million, correct?

A    Probably 11, but correct.

Q    Probably 11. And the outstanding to OCBC, who was the bank that extended the mortgage, as of 2019 was something like $8 million, correct?

A    I think 7.6, but thereabouts.

Q    7.6. What were the monthly mortgage repayments in 2014, Mr Andrla?

A    I think principal and interest was perhaps $35,000.

Q    Right.

A    To the best of my recollection.

Q    Your statement of affairs in the IVA has your declared income at $16,500. Would that be accurate?

A    It is probably accurate.

Q    Okay. Now, I am going to put it to you that given your heavy indebtedness in August 2014, you were in no possession (sic) ---no position to be lending money to Mr Villanueva. Agree or disagree?

A    I think I probably agree. I lent because he was a friend.

65     Based on the plaintiff’s admission of his many other pressing financial obligations in 2014, including the mortgage payments for his own home, I find it difficult to believe that he would have been able to extend a “friendly loan” to the defendant even if he had been willing to do so. On a balance of probabilities, I find that the plaintiff’s payment of $87,000 to the defendant was a partial repayment to discharge the 2011 Loan.

Could the 2011 Loan have ballooned to over $245,000 by 31 October 2014?

The plaintiff’s submissions

66     Counsel for the plaintiff, Mr Wee, spent a considerable time on this aspect of his case to disprove the defendant’s defence – the $87,000 disbursed to the defendant could not be a partial repayment to discharge the 2011 Loan as this would mean that the loan amount of $96,500 had ballooned to $245,000 by 31 October 2014, the date that the parties signed the Written Loan Agreement. The plaintiff had adopted the same arguments in his AEIC[note: 38].

67     To illustrate his point, Mr Wee had produced a table (exhibit ‘P-1’) to show that based on the interest rates charged on the three initial loans taken out by the defendant in 2011 which did not exceed 6.80% per annum at any time from March 2011 to August 2014, it was mathematically impossible for the 2011 Loan to balloon to the sum of $245,000[note: 39]. Working the sums backwards, the compounded interest rate levied would have gone to 29% per annum in order to reach this sum. However, the defendant has tendered no documentary evidence of the interest incurred on his loans from October 2011 to July 2014, much less that the interest on these loans exceeded 29%.

68     The plaintiff further contended that:

(a)     The defendant never explained the additional “further loans” he had allegedly taken or how the loans combined would result in an effective interest rate of 29% per annum. Instead, the defendant had made vague references to additional loans in the hope that this would “muddy the waters”.

(b)     The defendant’s pleaded case is that the plaintiff was only liable to repay the principal sum of the 2011 Loan plus any “financing interest” incurred. The interest in the Written Loan Agreement was set at 2% per month as that was the aggregate amount of interest that the defendant was incurring. The defendant had never made mention of any additional loans which, according to him, are responsible for the bulk of the interest incurred between March 2011 and October 2014.

(c)     Even if such additional loans had been taken, the effect would have been to enable the defendant to pay down the principal sums of the original loans thereby reducing the amount of interest payable.

The defendant’s submissions

69     Counsel for the defendant, Mr Choo, submitted that the 2011 Loan had indeed ballooned to $245,775 by 2014, and highlighted in particular the following[note: 40]:

(a)     The 2011 Loan was an arrangement in which the defendant took out several loans from various banks on the plaintiff’s behalf and on the plaintiff’s agreement to repay the loans together with their accompanying interest.

(b)     The plaintiff himself had accepted that the defendant had to borrow from various banks in order to extend the 2011 Loan, his dispute was only that the Loan was given to SAPL and not to him[note: 41].

(c)     The plaintiff knew, and had agreed, that the aggregated effective interest rate of the loans taken out by the defendant for the 2011 Loan was about 2% per month compounded monthly when he entered into the Written Loan Agreement. A monthly compounded interest rate of 2% per month gives an effective annual interest rate of 26.82%, which is very close to the 29% effective interest rate. In reality, the effective interest rate was slightly higher than the 2% because the defendant had to draw down more loans than he needed each time in anticipation of future repayments, as opposed to drawing down just enough for each repayment as they came due[note: 42].

(d)     The fundamental premise of the plaintiff’s calculations is that interest only accrued on a single, rolling amount of the original principal plus the accrued interest up to that point. However, as the defendant had explained at some length during cross-examination[note: 43], that fundamental premise is wrong because the defendant had to take out further loans to repay the initial loans.

(e)     The total outstanding amount upon which interest accrues each month would vary depending on the quantum of the additional loans taken out by the defendant.

(f)     The effective interest rate of 29% per annum, compounded monthly, is in fact perfectly consistent with the evidence before the court even though the defendant has not been able to furnish his bank records from 2011 to 2014[note: 44].

My finding

70     I accept the defendant’s evidence that the total amount under the 2011 Loan had snowballed because not only had he taken out the initial loans to extend the $96,500 to the plaintiff; he did in fact take out further loans to make the monthly repayments of the initial loans when the plaintiff failed to pay the required amounts. He then had to draw down on further loans to make the monthly repayments of the earlier loans taken out.

71     This was because the arrangement between the plaintiff and the defendant was effectively that the defendant would be taking out unsecured loans from financial institutions on the plaintiff’s behalf. The amount “snowballed” due to the plaintiff’s inability to make the repayments. The promotional rates of interest were only available for a limited time, as the defendant had explained[note: 45]. The payments for the loans were not meant to come out of the defendant’s own pocket because these loans were the plaintiff’s loans and the repayment was to come from the plaintiff alone[note: 46].

72     The defendant’s position has been comprehensively pleaded in the Further and Better Particulars served pursuant to the plaintiff’s request dated 30 June 2021 filed on 23 September 2021. He has also furnished a detailed list of the loans and repayments made from 4 August 2014 to 4 August 2016 in Schedule 1 to the Further and Better Particulars[note: 47]. Notably, the defendant had provided the plaintiff with a spreadsheet of the outstanding loans in August 2016 and the instalments payable. His email of 14 July 2016 had also set out how the sum of $158,775 as at 31 October 2014 had ballooned to $234,736.92 in July 2016. The following extract is particularly relevant to show how the sum would grow exponentially[note: 48]:

With reference to the loan agreement which was signed with you on 31 Oct 2014, the amount was for a sum of $158,775, which accrues at a monthly interest of 2% per month. At this rate, the amount owed today will be about $240,650 (21 months from date of loan agreement).

With the current arrangement, the monthly installments are $13,106.71. The remaining installments range from 6 months to 36 months (you can see the details in the attached sheet). If you were to pay all installments till the last one 36 months from now, the total outstanding will be $234,737. Of course, if you were to prepay the existing loans, this amount will be significantly smaller. Alternatively, if we were to take on more loans to repay the monthly loan obligations, the existing outstanding loan amount will balloon. Also, if these installments are not repaid on time, the loans will revert to a 24-36% p.a. rate which will be disastrous.

The amount above is much lower than the loan that accrues at 2% per month. If the current loan is left unpaid till 36 months from now, the outstanding loan owed will be $490,898. You can see where the problem is if this is left to fester.

73     The plaintiff had, at no time, disputed the magnitude of the outstanding loan as stated in the defendant’s email. He had in fact accepted this as a fact and had (as seen in the series of messages exhibited in the defendant’s AEIC) made some vain attempts to keep to the monthly payments of $13,000.

74     The defendant’s position that the initial loan of $96,500 in February/March 2011 had ballooned to over $245,000 in October 2014 is not as far-fetched as the plaintiff would want the court to believe. Going simply by way of a rough comparison, the loan of $158,775 as at 31 October 2014 had grown to $234,737 in 21 months. In the 44 months (from March 2011 to October 2014), if repayments were not made faithfully, it is certainly not inconceivable that the initial debt of $96,500 in 2011 had ballooned to $245,000 on account of the compounding interest.

75     When asked about the supporting documentary evidence, the defendant was also able to correlate the outstanding loans from the various banks detailed in his spreadsheet[note: 49] to the documents in his AEIC[note: 50]. He had clearly made concerted attempts to lower the repayment sum as much as possible to which no objections were raised at any time by the plaintiff.

76     In regard to the lack of documentary records from 2011 to 2014, the defendant has also given a reasonable and credible explanation. He was unable to obtain records beyond the seven years prior to the suit as the banks simply did not retain them. This has not been challenged by the plaintiff.

77     From all the available evidence, I find that the defendant has proven that the 2011 Loan given to the plaintiff would have ballooned to over $245,000 in October 2014. The plaintiff’s payment of $87,000 was in all probability a partial repayment of the 2011 Loan. After deducting the payment of $87,000, the outstanding sum as at 31 October 2014 was $158,775 as documented in the Written Loan Agreement signed by both parties.

Whether the 2nd Loan was a loan extended by the plaintiff to the defendant or a payment by the plaintiff of salaries owed by SAPL to the defendant

78     In his AEIC, the defendant had listed out several payments into his bank account which came directly from the plaintiff which he says were partial payments for his outstanding salaries owed by SAPL. The payments were:

(a)     $50,000 on 5 November 2014;

(b)     $30,000 on 24 December 2014;

(c)     $5,000 on 3 February 2015;

(d)     $5,000 on 4 February 2015; and

(e)     $5,000 on 13 March 2015.

79     The 2nd Loan which the plaintiff claims to be another friendly loan given to the defendant to alleviate his financial difficulty at the material time covers only the four payments made on 5 November 2014, 24 December 2014, 3 February 2015 and 13 March 2015. There is no evidence from the plaintiff to explain why he had paid the defendant $5,000 on 4 February 2015.

80     At the trial, it was also not put to the defendant that the $5,000 payment from the plaintiff on 4 February 2015 was not a payment of the defendant’s salaries owed by SAPL. I note that in the plaintiff’s reply submissions, Mr Wee had submitted that the defendant is precluded from relying on this point as it was omitted from the defendant’s pleadings. With respect, this is incorrect as details of the defendant’s salary payments had been included in Schedule 2 annexed to the Further and Better Particulars filed on 23 September 2021[note: 51]. As can be seen in the table, the defendant had stated that $10,000 had been received for the month of February 2015. This would correlate to the two payments of $5,000 each on 3 February and 4 February 2015.

81     The defendant’s elaboration of his salary payments has been set out in Tab 10 of his AEIC where he has specifically described the payments received in February 2015 as “DA bank transfers” as shown in his UOB statement being two transfers of $5,000 each[note: 52]. The plaintiff is not unaware of the defendant’s claim that the payment of $5,000 made on 4 February 2015 is the plaintiff’s part-payment of his salary from SAPL as this had been canvassed at the summary judgment proceedings taken out by the plaintiff in DC/SUM 2401/2020. Given the plaintiff’s failure to challenge the defendant’s position as regards the transfer he made on 4 February 2015, I have to agree with Mr Choo’s submission that there is an admission from the plaintiff that the $5,000 payment from him to the defendant on 4 February 2015 was a payment of the defendant’s salaries owed by SAPL on behalf of SAPL[note: 53].

82     The defendant has also given a credible account of how it came about that his salaries were halved for 2014 in order to extinguish SAPL’s salary debt to him. All this was done retrospectively at the point when the defendant resigned in April 2015. There is clear evidence in the defendant’s bank statements that SAPL made salary payments of $26,500 per month in 2014 for the months of January, February, May and June 2014[note: 54] albeit they were made in arrears.

83     The plaintiff’s account that they had agreed to halve the defendant’s salary in September 2014 purportedly after SAPL lost the Behringer litigation in the Court of Appeal is also at odds with the records furnished by his solicitors which show that it was only on 26 November 2014 that the matter was dealt with and concluded.

84     In any case, the defendant has provided a reasonable and credible explanation of how the sum of $153,000 was derived after factoring in the $95,000 paid by the plaintiff. Given that the parties were still on amicable terms in April 2015, the defendant had agreed to write it off, and the three months’ notice period stipulated in his employment agreement was waived by the plaintiff on SAPL’s behalf since SAPL was in no position to pay him any further salaries.

85     As for the plaintiff treating himself as the alter ego of SAPL, this has been clearly demonstrated by his conduct in the IVA where he had conveniently accepted the 2011 Loan as his debt which was extinguished by the Nominee’s acceptance of the defendant’s proof of debt.

86     Given the parties’ long relationship from 1998, and the fact that the plaintiff was the sole shareholder and director of SAPL[note: 55], it is certainly within reasonable contemplation that the plaintiff would treat his and SAPL’s funds as interchangeable which I find to be the case here. Set against the plaintiff’s increasing liability to the defendant under the Written Loan Agreement, there is no other credible explanation why there would be fund transfers from the plaintiff’s personal account for the sums claimed as the alleged 2nd Loan apart from these being payments of the defendant’s outstanding salaries.

Plaintiff failed to discharge his burden of proof that a 2nd Loan was given

87     At the end of the day, the plaintiff has to show to the court that he had extended friendly loans to the defendant and made requests for their repayment. As admitted by the plaintiff, there is no such evidence (apart from his bare assertions) other than the claim pleaded in this action, as he also conceded in cross-examination[note: 56]:

Q    Yes. Because you have referred to several demands for repayment. I assume this must be somewhere in your evidence that you had asked Mr Villanueva: please return this $177,000 that I have lent you, correct?

A    These were oral requests to Mr Villanueva.

Q    So, no written requests?

A    No. No written requests prior to litigation. No.

Q    No text messages of any sort?

A    No. I don’t think so.

88     Where a plaintiff claims that he has extended a loan to a defendant for which he seeks judgment, the burden of proof must surely be on that plaintiff to establish the existence of the loan, see s 103(1) Evidence Act 1893:

103. –(1) Whoever desires any court to give judgment as to any legal right or liability, dependent on the existence of facts which the person asserts, must prove that those facts exist.

89     In the present case, the plaintiff’s entire litigation strategy was in essence an attempt on his part to disprove the defendant’s defence which he has failed to do. The defendant has given a comprehensive account of the parties’ dealings with each other and produced all the relevant documents to support his defences whereas the plaintiff has relied only on his oral assertions. The plaintiff has failed to discharge his burden of proof.

Conclusion

For the foregoing reasons, the plaintiff’s claim is hereby dismissed with costs. On the issue of costs, the parties are directed to file their respective written submissions within 14 days from the release of this judgment for the court’s consideration.
